  {
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "```powershell\r\nPS C:\\ProgramData\\kasini3000> 1..3 | ForEach-Object -ThrottleLimit 1 -Parallel { cmd /k exit 1; Write-Host $? }\r\nFalse\r\nTrue\r\nTrue\r\nPS C:\\ProgramData\\kasini3000> 1..3 | ForEach-Object -ThrottleLimit 1 -Parallel { cmd /k exit 1; Write-Host $? } -UseNewRunspace\r\nFalse\r\nFalse\r\nFalse\r\n\r\nPS C:\\ProgramData\\kasini3000> $PSVersionTable\r\n\r\nName                           Value\r\n----                           -----\r\nPSVersion                      7.3.0-preview.1\r\nPSEdition                      Core\r\nGitCommitId                    7.3.0-preview.1\r\nOS                             Microsoft Windows 10.0.19044\r\nPlatform                       Win32NT\r\nPSCompatibleVersions           {1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0…}\r\nPSRemotingProtocolVersion      2.3\r\nSerializationVersion           1.1.0.1\r\nWSManStackVersion              3.0\r\n\r\n```\r\nLook at the manual to know：\r\n\r\n### -UseNewRunspace\r\n\r\nIn PowerShell 7, a new runspace is created for each loop iteration to ensure maximum isolation. This can have a large performance and resource penalty.\r\nStarting with PowerShell 7.1, runspaces in the runspace pool will be reused by default. This results in good performance but poor isolation. You can still use the UseNewRunspace switch to create a new runspace for each iteration.",
